---
/*
 * S06Orchestrator.astro — The Orchestrator section
 *
 * Two-zone layout (iyo-clean pattern):
 *   Entry:  Eyebrow "THE ORCHESTRATOR" (azure) + BlurReveal headline + lead
 *   Body:   3 paragraphs — runtime privilege gap, what that enables, why by design
 *           Sub-section: 7-step common pattern (NumberedRows)
 *
 * background="void"   mode="technical" (azure eyebrow)
 * Content sourced from: .design/sections/06-orchestrator.md
 */
import Section from '../components/sections/Section.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/content/Eyebrow.astro';
import BlurReveal from '../components/content/BlurReveal.astro';
import NumberedRow from '../components/content/NumberedRow.astro';
import UpNextTeaser from '../components/content/UpNextTeaser.astro';
---

<Section id="s6" label="The Orchestrator" background="void">
  <Fragment slot="entry">
    <Eyebrow label="THE ORCHESTRATOR" mode="technical" />
    <BlurReveal>
      <h2>One module gets live access to the full system at runtime. Every other module is isolated after setup.</h2>
    </BlurReveal>
    <p class="lead">
      Every other module is isolated after mount. The Orchestrator gets the Coordinator at
      runtime, on every call. That privilege gap defines how the entire agent loop works.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- ── Body ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="body">
    <p>
      Every module in Amplifier receives the Coordinator (the registry where modules are
      stored) once: at mount time. The module uses it to register itself, and then the
      Coordinator reference is gone.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Orchestrator is the exception. It receives the Coordinator again, at runtime, every
      time it's called. This means the Orchestrator can, at any moment during execution, reach
      into the registry and access any module: the Context Manager, every Provider, every Tool,
      every Hook Handler.
    </p>
    <p>
      No other module can do this. A Provider can't look up which Tools are available. A Tool
      can't check which Provider is being used. Only the Orchestrator has a live connection to
      the full system at runtime. This is by design, not by accident.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Common pattern: 7 steps ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="pattern">
    <h3>One common pattern: what happens when you send a message</h3>
    <p class="pattern__intro">
      This shows one commonly used orchestrator. Different orchestrators can implement
      completely different strategies.
    </p>

    <div class="pattern__steps">
      <NumberedRow
        number="01"
        label="You send a message"
        description="The session receives it and hands it to the Orchestrator."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="02"
        label="Hooks fire; context monitoring begins"
        description="A context monitor hook might notice the conversation involves database queries and inject the relevant schema documentation."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="03"
        label="Orchestrator fetches context"
        description="Calls the Context Manager to get conversation history (what's been said, what tools have been used)."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="04"
        label="Provider calls the AI model"
        description="The Orchestrator calls a Provider. The Provider sends the assembled context to the AI model and waits for a response."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="05"
        label="If the AI wants a tool, hooks check first"
        description="Before the tool executes, an event fires. Hook Handlers can observe, modify, or block the call. A safety hook might say 'that tool call is trying to delete system files. Denied.' If no hook blocks the call, the tool executes."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="06"
        label="After the tool runs, hooks inject feedback"
        description="A code quality hook might run after a file-writing tool, find issues, and inject 'The code checker found 3 issues in lines 12, 15, and 22.' The AI reads this on its next iteration."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="07"
        label="The Orchestrator returns the response"
        description="Rich data (token usage, tool history) flows through the event system for any hooks that want to observe it."
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  <img
    src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}diagrams/reasoning-loop.svg`}
    alt="Orchestrator reasoning loop: Think, Act, Observe, Decide"
    class="diagram"
  />

  <UpNextTeaser
    nextSection="Tools vs Hooks"
    teaser="Tools are capabilities the AI controls. Hooks control the AI without it knowing."
  />
</Section>

<style>
  /* ── Entry zone ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  h2 {
    max-width: 20ch;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 55ch;
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }

  /* ── Body ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 60ch;
    color: var(--text-body);
  }

  .body p {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  /* ── Common pattern ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .pattern {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 60ch;
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  .pattern h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .pattern__intro {
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
    color: var(--text-body);
  }

  .pattern__steps {
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  /* ── Diagram ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .diagram {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
    opacity: 0.9;
  }
</style>
